<webwork-reps version="2" webwork2_major_version="2" webwork2_minor_version="20" xml:id="extracted-section-multiplication-and-division-of-rational-expressions-7-2-9" assembly-id="section-multiplication-and-division-of-rational-expressions-7-2-9">
  <static seed="1122" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/Factoring/factoring390.pg">
    <statement><p>Factor the given polynomial.</p>
<p><m>{8x^{7}+24x^{6}+16x^{5}}=</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>8x^{5}\mathopen{}\left(x+2\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>Let<rsq/>s start by noting that <m>8x^{5}</m> is a common factor to each term, so 
we may write</p>
<p><m>{8x^{7}+24x^{6}+16x^{5}}={8x^{5}\mathopen{}\left(x^{2}+3x+2\right)}</m></p>
<p>To factor this expression further we make the following observations:
<ul label="disc">
<li>
<p>the leading coefficient is 1</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>the middle term<rsq/>s coefficient and the last term are <em>positive</em> which means that the factorization
will have the form</p>
<p><m>(x+\phantom{3})(x+\phantom{3})</m></p>
</li>
</ul></p>
<p>We look for factors of <m>2</m> that add to <m>3</m>; the 
factors that work are <m>2</m> and <m>1</m> so</p>
<p><m>{8x^{7}+24x^{6}+16x^{5}}={8x^{5}\mathopen{}\left(x+2\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)}</m></p>
<p>Note that this answer can be checked by using the FOIL (<alert>F</alert>irst <alert>O</alert>utside <alert>I</alert>nside <alert>L</alert>ast) technique (exercise).</p>
</solution>
